    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Boston Jan 21&#47;83<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais.<lb/>
                Respected Sir.<lb/></p>
            <p>Your postal<lb/> and contents to hand and in reply<lb/> I would say <sic>That</sic> some time<lb/> ago I wrote a letter to the secre&#45;<lb/>tary of the United Hebrew<lb/> Benevolent society of Philadel&#45;<lb/>phia upon a matter which I<lb/> shall herein relate and<lb/> received no reply. I was advised<lb/> by Mr. A. Marcus of this city to<lb/> address you in the matter and<lb/> do so with the hope that any<lb/> trouble it will occasion&#44; will be<lb/> considered by you as for the good<lb/> of Judaism.<lb/></p>
            <p>About two years ago&#44; the wife<lb/> of Samuel Harris was on her<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>voyage from London to New York<lb/> and died on the passage she<lb/> had with her 4 children.  On<lb/> their arrival the fathre took<lb/> charge of the children and<lb/> placed 2 in the Orphan<lb/> Asylum in New York taking<lb/> 2 with him in Philadelphia.<lb/>  Shortly after the affair occurred<lb/> he got married and treated his<lb/> family very badly at one time<lb/> being arrested for the same.<lb/>  By his cruelty he drove his<lb/> eldest daughter aged 14 from the house.<lb/></p>                 <p>Being driven from home his<lb/> daughter Sarah was taken into<lb/> the House of Industry&#44; and<lb/> from there taken by a Catholic<lb/> family to West Philadelphia<lb/> where she is to stay until she<lb/> reaches the age of 21 years.<lb/></p>
            <p>If she should remain with<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>the Christians for that length of<lb/> time she would naturally lose<lb/> all faith in our belief&#44; having<lb/> continually before her eyes the<lb/> example of her Christian protectors.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am by marriage the brother<lb/> in law of Mrs Harris&#44; besides<lb/> the grandmother being here&#44; we<lb/> desire to obtain custody of the<lb/> child so that we may bring<lb/> her up as our own and so that<lb/> she may not stray or be forced<lb/> from the fold of Judaism.  Though<lb/> but a poor man and having a<lb/> large family I would endeavor<lb/> to give her all the comforts my<lb/> own children possess and provide<lb/> for her as for them as a father.<lb/></p>
            <p>To this end I write to you&#44;<lb/> trusting that you will do all<lb/> you can to comply with our<lb/> wishes&#44; were I pecuniarily able<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>I would go on to Philadelphia<lb/> myself but my circumstances<lb/> will not allow of it.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping you will meet with<lb/> success in procuring for me<lb/> custody of the child I remain<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours Very Respectfully<lb/>
                Solomon Bloom.<lb/>
                31 Pilestone St.<lb/></p>
            <p>P. S. Should any references be<lb/> required I can furnish them.<lb/>  Please answer and inform me<lb/> what you can do in the matter.<lb/></p>
        </body>
